<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1144,1673]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Valves lanceolate to linear-lanceolate with narrowly rostrate apices. Pseudosepta absent. Valve length 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.2" metricValueMax="7.6" metricValueMin="4.8" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" unit="mm" value="62.0" valueMax="76.0" valueMin="48.0">48–76 µm</quantity>
; valve width 
<quantity box="[359,487,1183,1209]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.35" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="1.2" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" unit="mm" value="13.5" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="12.0">12–15 µm</quantity>
. Raphe lateral, straight with weakly inflated proximal ends. Distal raphe ends hooked to same side. Axial area 3 x wider than raphe, expanding slightly near central area. Central stauros narrow, nearly rectangular, hardly expanding towards valve margins where shortened striae may be present. Striae radiate throughout, 
<quantity box="[456,559,1298,1324]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.08" metricValueMax="5.334" metricValueMin="4.826" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" unit="in" value="20.0" valueMax="21.0" valueMin="19.0">19–21 in</quantity>
<quantity box="[567,646,1298,1324]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" unit="mm" value="10.0">10 µm</quantity>
. Areolae in striae 
<quantity box="[859,956,1298,1324]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.096" metricValueMax="7.112" metricValueMin="5.08" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" unit="in" value="24.0" valueMax="28.0" valueMin="20.0">20-28 in</quantity>
<quantity box="[964,1044,1298,1324]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" unit="mm" value="10.0">10 µm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1144,1673]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,333,1337,1363]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Etymology</emphasis>
:— 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bahls" authorityYear="2012" box="[371,651,1337,1362]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Stauroneidaceae" genus="Stauroneis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="spauldingiae">
<emphasis box="[371,651,1337,1362]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Stauroneis spauldingiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is named after Sarah Spaulding, a modern day explorer of diatoms, distant lands, and big rock walls.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1144,1673]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,374,1414,1440]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Observations:</emphasis>
— 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bahls" authorityYear="2012" box="[403,692,1415,1440]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Stauroneidaceae" genus="Stauroneis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="spauldingiae">
<emphasis box="[403,692,1415,1440]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Stauroneis spauldingiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was reported by 
<bibRefCitation author="Bahls, L." box="[920,1130,1415,1441]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" refId="ref3484" refString="Bahls, L. (2010) Stauroneis in the Northern Rockies - 50 species of Stauroneis sensu stricto from western Montana, northern Idaho, northeastern Washington and southwestern Alberta, including 16 species described as new. Vol. 4 In: Bahls, L. (Ed.), Northwest Diatoms, Montana Diatom Collection, Helena, 179 pp." type="book" year="2010">Bahls (2010: 45)</bibRefCitation>
as 
<taxonomicName authority="Ehrenberg (1843: 34)" authorityName="Ehrenberg" authorityPageNumber="34" authorityYear="1843" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Stauroneidaceae" genus="Stauroneis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="anceps">
<emphasis box="[1183,1300,1415,1440]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">S. anceps</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Ehrenberg" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" pagination="291 - 445" refId="ref3648" refString="Ehrenberg (1843) Verbreitung und Einfluss des mikroskopischen Lebens in Sud- und Nord-Amerika. Abhandlungen der Koniglichen Akademie der Wissenschaften zu Berlin, 1841: 291 - 445, 4 Tafel." type="book chapter" year="1843">Ehrenberg (1843: 34)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. Valves of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bahls" authorityYear="2012" box="[406,587,1454,1479]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Stauroneidaceae" genus="Stauroneis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="spauldingiae">
<emphasis box="[406,587,1454,1479]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">S. spauldingiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are somewhat larger, and have a lower stria density and a smaller, more rectangular stauros than specimens designated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Reichardt, E." box="[737,982,1492,1518]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" pagination="1 - 99" refId="ref4299" refString="Reichardt, E. (1995) Die Diatomeen (Bacillariophyceae) in Ehrenbergs Material von Cayenne, Guyana Gallica (1843). Vol. 1 In: Lange-Bertalot, H. (Ed.), Iconographia Diatomologica, Koeltz Scientific Books, Konigstein, pp. 1 - 99." type="book chapter" year="1995">Reichardt (1995: 25)</bibRefCitation>
as the 
<typeStatus box="[1064,1171,1492,1518]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">lectotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ehrenberg" authorityYear="1843" box="[1212,1322,1492,1517]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Stauroneidaceae" genus="Stauroneis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="anceps">
<emphasis box="[1212,1322,1492,1517]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">S. anceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Sippe 1, Tafel 16, 
<figureCitation box="[270,397,1530,1556]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 1–8" captionStart-1="FIGURES 9–24" captionStartId-0="2.[151,259,1714,1735]" captionStartId-1="4.[151,257,1904,1925]" captionTargetBox-0="[239,1335,214,1672]" captionTargetBox-1="[194,1365,377,1800]" captionTargetId-0="figure-67@2.[231,1355,197,1689]" captionTargetId-1="figure-140@4.[188,1398,372,1884]" captionTargetPageId-0="2" captionTargetPageId-1="4" captionText-0="FIGURES 1–8: Stauroneis clarkii and Stauroneis lewisii. Figs 1–4: Stauroneis clarkii from the type locality. Figs 5–8: Stauroneis lewisii from various locations. Figs 5–6: Blodgett Lake, Selway-Bitterroot Wilderness, Montana (type locality). Fig. 7: Fred Burr Lake, Selway-Bitterroot Wilderness, Montana. Fig. 8: Bloody Dick Pond No. 6, Beaverhead County, Montana." captionText-1="FIGURES 9–24: Stauroneis sacajaweae, S. spauldingiae, and S. thompsonii. Figs 9–15: Stauroneis sacajaweae. Figs 9, 11–15: Type locality. Fig. 10: Haystack Seep, Going-To-The-Sun Road, Glacier National Park, Montana. Figs 16–21: Stauroneis spauldingiae. Figs 16–18, 20, 21: Copper Lake, Shoshone County, Idaho (type locality). Fig. 19: Lily Lake, Lemhi County, Idaho. Figs 22–24: Stauroneis thompsonii from the type locality." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5065936" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5065938" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/5065936/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/5065938/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Figs 1–12</figureCitation>
). The occurrence of 
<emphasis box="[656,800,1531,1556]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ehrenberg" authorityYear="1843" box="[656,768,1531,1556]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Stauroneidaceae" genus="Stauroneis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="anceps">S. anceps</taxonomicName>
—
</emphasis>
one of the most frequently misidentified species of 
<emphasis box="[151,303,1569,1594]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<taxonomicName authorityName="C. G. Ehrenberg" authorityYear="1843" box="[151,272,1569,1594]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Stauroneidaceae" genus="Stauroneis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="genus">Stauroneis</taxonomicName>
—
</emphasis>
remains to be confirmed in the 
<collectingCountry box="[682,745,1569,1595]" name="United States of America" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">USA</collectingCountry>
. In addition to the type locality, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bahls" authorityYear="2012" box="[1138,1323,1569,1594]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Stauroneidaceae" genus="Stauroneis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="spauldingiae">
<emphasis box="[1138,1323,1569,1594]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">S. spauldingiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been collected from several small lakes and ponds in western 
<collectingRegion box="[838,944,1608,1634]" country="United States of America" name="Montana" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Montana</collectingRegion>
and northern 
<collectingRegion box="[1115,1183,1608,1634]" country="United States of America" name="Idaho" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Idaho</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Bahls, L." box="[1200,1343,1608,1634]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" refId="ref3484" refString="Bahls, L. (2010) Stauroneis in the Northern Rockies - 50 species of Stauroneis sensu stricto from western Montana, northern Idaho, northeastern Washington and southwestern Alberta, including 16 species described as new. Vol. 4 In: Bahls, L. (Ed.), Northwest Diatoms, Montana Diatom Collection, Helena, 179 pp." type="book" year="2010">Bahls 2010</bibRefCitation>
). These waters have circumneutral pH and very low concentrations of dissolved solids.
</paragraph>
